><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/E8C68F77-A46E-476E-9643-1FAC05331701"><gtr:id>E8C68F77-A46E-476E-9643-1FAC05331701</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Christopher</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>John</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Ballentine</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/0B2BF911-DBCC-4F8F-9BC8-DB7C482B0127"><gtr:id>0B2BF911-DBCC-4F8F-9BC8-DB7C482B0127</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Clare</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Florence</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Postlethwaite</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=NE%2FD002478%2F1"><gtr:id>16860805-A3D4-43CF-9C60-E215F71D3A86</gtr:id><gtr:title>Attribution of climate change in the subtropical North Atlantic Ocean: exploiting tritium-helium data and adjoint sensitivity analyses</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>NE/D002478/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>There is uncertainity in how the North Atlantic operates in the climate system in terms of its heat content and biological export of organic matter, which ultimately affects how the ocean uptakes excess carbon from the atmosphere. For example, over the last 50 years, there has been an increase in heat content in the subtropical North Atlantic, associated with an increase in volume of both upper thermocline water (18 to 24C) and cold thermocline waters (4 to 10C), but a decrease in other neighbouring temperature classes. This proposal aims to understand how the subtropical North Atlantic operates in the climate system by analysing tritium-helium observations along 36N and 25W across the basin. The inferred tritium-helium age provides a measure of the elapsed time since the water was last in contact with the atmosphere. The measurements of tritium-helium age will be used to understand: 1. How ventilation controls the observed changes in heat content in the subtropical North Atlantic; 2. To identify the rate of export of organic matter which is diagnosed indirectly from the rate of oxygen utilisation using the tritium-helium age. The reliability of the data signals will be assessed by comparying with a circulation model and its adjoint. The sensitivity of the climate change, the export of organic matter and cycling of nutrients, will then be understood by using the same model and its adjoint, which efficiently identifies the effect of changes in external forcing and model physics.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-08-22</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/8A03ED41-E67D-4F4A-B5DD-AAFB272B6471"><gtr:id>8A03ED41-E67D-4F4A-B5DD-AAFB272B6471</gtr:id><gtr:name>NERC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-05-23</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>249054</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have discovered reversing sign patterns of large-scale ocean heat content. Often when the subtropical North Atlantic is anomalously warm, the subpolar North Atlantic is cool and vice versa. 

In a similar manner, we have found that the anomalies in the meridional overturning circulation often have opposing signs in the subtropical and subpolar latitudes of the North Atlantic, contrary to expectations.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>There have been follow up NERC grants to explain why this reversing heat content pattern often forms in the North Atlantic. For example, the international Overturning in the Subpolar North Atlantic Programme (OSNAP) has drawn upon this work, involving a total of &amp;pound;30M of international investment from the US, UK, Germany, Canada, the Netherlands and China.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>B76918B5-C3F6-4806-90A8-ED781BB83EE7</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLb-tDwhZ4KsW3nGt7iClxszS-4QbERUJ8</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/66573A42-15AA-4B61-AB1B-172841D33704"><gtr:id>66573A42-15AA-4B61-AB1B-172841D33704</gtr:id><gtr:title>Meridional coherence of the North Atlantic meridional overturning circulation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Geophysical Research Letters</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/2dd44105434743a9c713b7a795592746"><gtr:id>2dd44105434743a9c713b7a795592746</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bingham R</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2007-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/8C876804-DBE0-4FCA-9B8E-2B8CA7CB5CE5"><gtr:id>8C876804-DBE0-4FCA-9B8E-2B8CA7CB5CE5</gtr:id><gtr:title>Opposing decadal changes for the North Atlantic meridional overturning circulation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicat